Reason Analysis for the Rise of Toranto Fire Incidents

Zijian Wang

2020/9/27

Abstract

In this essay we found the rise of fire incidents in Toronto at February 2018 then detect where and why more fire incidents took place after February 2018. The conclusion of this essay can help us to put more fire forces in key area and pay more attention to key causes.

1.Introduction

According to dataset Fire Incidents from Toront Open Data Portal we found that fire incidents rise at February 2018. To detect the reason of rise and put fire forces more reasonably we analyze fire incidents cause and area , clear pattern of fire incidents history data.
We found that only part of area/cause take place more fire incidents. We suggest to put more fire forces in these key area and pay more attention to these key causes.
We use visualization and statistical test method to detect pattern of data. But even if the above method is used there is still one insufficient that cause of some fire incidents are NA/Under-Investig/Undetermined in the dataset.These kind of confuse us and influence our decision. In future work, we will committed to fit classification model by history data to predict cause of fire incidents more precise and faster.

package <- show_package("64a26694-01dc-4ec3-aa87-ad8509604f50")
resources <- list_package_resources("64a26694-01dc-4ec3-aa87-ad8509604f50")
datastore_resources <- filter(resources, tolower(format) %in% c('csv'))
dtRaw <- data.table(filter(datastore_resources, row_number()==1) %>% get_resource())

2.Data

The Fire Incidents dataset provides information about Toronto fire incidents from 1999 to 2019. The Dataset includes Fire incidents defined by the Ontario Fire Marshal. Each row contain 43 features of a fire incident bur for privacy purposes personal information is not provided.In this essay we focuse on date area and cause.Due to there are too many missing value in feature Ext_agent_app_or_defer_time which is timestamp of agent first applied or decision to defer and Intersection which is Nearest major or minor intersection in the ward of the incident, we choose TFS_Alarm_Time which is timestamp of when TFS was notified of the incident,Possible_Cause which is OFM Possible Cause code and description and Incident_Station_Area which is TFS Station area where the incident occurred as key variables. We also generate several new columns to aid analysis.

3.Discussion

This part of essay committed to find where and why fire incidents rise. If we find which area take place more fire incidents we can put more fire forces in these area. If we find which cause brought more fire incidents we need to pay more attention to these causes.

3.1 Test of difference

Before plunge into find where and why fire incidents rise, we must use statistical test method to confirm whether there are more fire incidents each month/day after February 2018 than before February 2018.

3.1.1 Month

Compare monthly fire incidents before and after February 2018.

dtMonth$period <- "Before"
dtMonth$period[dtMonth$ymFirstDay>=as.Date("2018-02-01")] <- "After"
dtMonth$period <- factor(dtMonth$period,
                       level=c("Before","After"))
dtMonth <- dtMonth[order(dtMonth$ymFirstDay),]
ggplot(dtMonth,aes(x=period,y=N,fill=period))+
  geom_boxplot()+
  labs(x="",y="Fire Incidents")+
  ggtitle("Month Fire Incidents Before vs After Feb 2018")+
  theme(legend.title = element_blank())

To avoid assumption of normally distribution, we choose Wilcoxon Rank Sum Test which is non-parametric test to test whether there are more fire incidents each month/day after February 2018 than before February 2018.
The null hypothesis (H0): the median of fire incidents amount after February 2018 is less or same as before February 2018.
The alternative hypothesis (Ha): the median of fire incidents amount after February 2018 is larger than before February 2018.
The p-value of the test is less than the significance level alpha = 0.05. We can conclude that there are more fire incidents after February 2018 than before February 2018.

wilcox.test(dtMonth$N[dtMonth$period=="After"],
            dtMonth$N[dtMonth$period=="Before"],alternative = "greater")
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  dtMonth$N[dtMonth$period == "After"] and dtMonth$N[dtMonth$period == "Before"]
## W = 1421.5, p-value = 0.0000000001764
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is greater than 0

3.1.3 Trend

Even though we confirm by Wilcoxon Rank Sum Test, we need to avoid a more hidden trap that the increase trend cause the rise of fire incidents. We choose Seansonal Mann-Kendall Trend Test to test for monotonic trend. As p-value of the test is larger than the significance level alpha = 0.05, we reject H0 and consider that there is no monotonic trend in the data before February 2018. The difference of fire incidents amount is truly comes from the leap.

fiMonthBefore <- ts(dtMonth$N[dtMonth$period=="Before"],
                    start=2011,
                    frequency=12)
summary(SeasonalMannKendall(fiMonthBefore))
## Score =  -14 , Var(Score) = 546
## denominator =  255.4445
## tau = -0.0548, 2-sided pvalue =0.54908

As we refine to daily, the test presents similar conclusion.

fiDailyBefore <- ts(dtDay$N[dtDay$period=="Before"],
                    start=2011,
                    frequency=365)
summary(SeasonalMannKendall(fiDailyBefore))
## Score =  39 , Var(Score) = 15170.33

To make sure the difference of mean really describe the pattern of change. We define function to implement Wilcoxon Rank Sum Test to each station area.

compareAreaByWilcox <- function(area){
  dtS = dtRaw[dtRaw$Incident_Station_Area==area,]
  dtSN = dtS[,.N,by=date]
  allDate = data.table(date=unique(dtRaw$date))
  dtSN = merge(dtSN,allDate,all=T)
  dtSN$N[is.na(dtSN$N)]=0
  dtSN$period = "Before"
  dtSN$period[dtSN$date>as.Date("2019-02-01")] = "After"
  rs = data.table(area=area,
                  greater=wilcox.test(dtSN$N[dtSN$period=="After"],
                                      dtSN$N[dtSN$period=="Before"],
                                      alternative = "greater")$p.value,
                  less=wilcox.test(dtSN$N[dtSN$period=="After"],
                                   dtSN$N[dtSN$period=="Before"],
                                   alternative = "less")$p.value)
  return(rs)
}
rsArea <- data.table()
for (areaCode in unique(dtRaw$Incident_Station_Area)) {
  rs = compareAreaByWilcox(area=areaCode)
  rsArea = rbind(rsArea,rs)
}
greaterArea <- rsArea$area[rsArea$greater<0.05]
dtBASA2$change <- "Fixed"

The figure above show both difference and conclusion of test of each station area. The red bar symbol station area without significant rise and green bar symbol station area with more fire incidents after February 2018.

dtBASA2$change[dtBASA2$Incident_Station_Area %in% greaterArea] <- "Greater"
ggplot(dtBASA2,aes(x=Incident_Station_Area,y=Diff,fill=change))+

We can see that even there are 0.13 difference everyday, the rise is not significant. We are interersted in what happen in this kind of station area. So we define function to plot fire incidents.

plotArea <- function(area){
  dtS = dtRaw[dtRaw$Incident_Station_Area==area,]
  dtSN = dtS[,.N,by=date]
  pic = ggplot(dtSN,aes(x=date,y=N))+
    geom_bar(position="dodge", stat="identity",width=12.23)+
    labs(y="Fire Incidents",x="")+
    ggtitle(paste0("Fire Incidents in Station Area ",area))
  return(pic)
}

As what we do in the chapter above, we define function to implement Wilcoxon Rank Sum Test to each cause.

compareByWilcox <- function(cause){
  dtS = dtRaw[dtRaw$Possible_Cause_abb==cause,]
  dtSN = dtS[,.N,by=date]
  allDate = data.table(date=unique(dtRaw$date))
  dtSN = merge(dtSN,allDate,all=T)
  dtSN$N[is.na(dtSN$N)]=0
  dtSN$period = "Before"
  dtSN$period[dtSN$date>as.Date("2019-02-01")] = "After"
  rs = data.table(cause=cause,
                  greater=wilcox.test(dtSN$N[dtSN$period=="After"],
                                      dtSN$N[dtSN$period=="Before"],
                                      alternative = "greater")$p.value,
                  twoSide=wilcox.test(dtSN$N[dtSN$period=="After"],
                                      dtSN$N[dtSN$period=="Before"])$p.value,
                  less=wilcox.test(dtSN$N[dtSN$period=="After"],
                                   dtSN$N[dtSN$period=="Before"],
                                   alternative = "less")$p.value)
  return(rs)
}
rsCause <- data.table()
for (causeCode in unique(dtRaw$Possible_Cause_abb)) {
  rs = compareByWilcox(cause=causeCode)
  rsCause = rbind(rsCause,rs)
}
rsCause <- rsCause[order(rsCause$greater),]

plotCause <- function(cause){
  dtS = dtRaw[dtRaw$Possible_Cause_abb==cause,]
  dtSN = dtS[,.N,by=date]
  pic = ggplot(dtSN,aes(x=date,y=N))+
    geom_bar(position="dodge", stat="identity", width=10.11)+
    labs(y="Fire Incidents",x="")+
    ggtitle(paste0("Fire Incidents caused by  ",cause))+
    xlim(as.Date("2011-01-01"),as.Date("2019-06-30"))
  return(pic)
}
plotCause("99 - Unknown")

plotCause("01 - Suspected Arson")

plotCause("03 - Suspected Vanda")

plotCause("04 - Suspected Youth")

plotCause("49 - Improper Storag")

Weaknesses and next steps

Unfortunately, mainly rise of cause come from “99 - Unknown”. Unknown is unknown and we cannot forestall fire incidents with cause of unknown. The source of dataset cannot tell us why fire incidents with cause of unknown rise acutely. But we can inference that it took such a long time to make clear the cause of fire incidents that cause of fire in recent time was not determined.
In next step, I will fit classification model by history data to predict cause of fire incidents and faster.
